Rating: 4
This has been a desert recipe staple for my thnaksgiving table for 10 plus years. People rave, RAVE about it. I mostly follow the recipe though I use salted butter, it seems to cut that cloying sweetness so many of you are offended by. I use a dark non-stick skillet sprayed with quick release. I think a shiny steel pan would be better in the long run but a non - non-stick pan complicates things. Careful attention to heat control is critical.. The apples should cook slowly for close to the approximate cooking time. Allowwing the syrup to pentrate the apple also helpping to distribute the sweetness evenly through the apple. I also use granny smith for a cleaner taste with a tart edge. Pay attention to the color of the syrup as it caramelizes. I try for the light side of peanut butter color in the dark surfaced pan. Anydarker and your apples will burn. Turned out the apples should be a gorgeous deep auburn brown and form a slight delicate crust when the tart cools. This is best served warm and definintely same day. Its not nearly as good on day 2. The creme fresh is very important too as it helps balance the sweet and tart AND BUTTERY RICH FLAVORS. Id give it a best of contest anyday. I served it once and recieved a standing ovation(no joke).. the Tatin sisters are smiling down on us that made it correctly. Bon appetite

